\begin_layout Standard
Here we remind the equations for skydips to understand a possible way out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resonance frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{r}$
\end_inset

 is linearly related to the total power on the kid, as represented by the
 equivalent temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{sky}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{r}=f_{0}-B\,T_{sky}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the zero-load frequency and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the response to total beam in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hz/K}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equivalent sky temperature is proportional to the total power on the
 Kid so that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{sky}=T_{atm}\frac{\int d\nu\,b_{\nu}(1-\exp(-\tau_{\nu}/\sin el)}{\int d\nu\,b_{\nu}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{atm}$
\end_inset

 is the mean atmosphere temperature (usually taken as a fiducial temperature
 of 270
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

K), 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the transmission (including the RJ 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{2}$
\end_inset

 which is compensated by the étendue), 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the zenith sky opacity and 
\begin_inset Formula $el$
\end_inset

 is the current skydip elevation (and the airmass is 
\begin_inset Formula $am=1/\sin el$
\end_inset

).
 In the standard skydip hypothesis, the opacity is rather constant across
 the filtering bandpass of the Kid (including the filters) so that we can
 drop the integral and get: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{sky}\backsimeq T_{atm}(1-\exp(-\tau/\sin el)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the opacity is small, the degeneracy of the response 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with the opacity 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is large.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is large, one can distinguish (with a non-linear fit) the influence of
 the response and the opacity.
 
\end_layout

